#: ../../manual/modeling/surfaces/introduction.rst:4
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr "简介"

#: ../../manual/modeling/surfaces/introduction.rst:6
msgid ""
"Curves are 2D objects, and surfaces are their 3D extension. Note however, that in Blender, you only have NURBS surfaces, no Bézier (you have the *Bézier* knot type, though; see below), nor polygonal (but for these, you have meshes!). Even though "
"curves and surfaces share the same object type (with texts also...), they are not the same thing; for example, you cannot have in the same object both curves and surfaces."
msgstr ""
"曲线是2D物体, 而曲面是他们的3D扩展. 但是请注意,在Blender中,你只能创建NURBS曲面,没有贝塞尔曲面(但你可以创建 *贝塞尔* 节点类型,见下文),也没有多边形曲面(但是对于这些,你可以创建网格). 虽然曲线和曲面共有相同的对象类型(和同样的文本等...)，但他们是不是同一"
"回事；例如，你不能在同一个物体里既有曲线又有曲面。"

#: ../../manual/modeling/surfaces/introduction.rst:17
msgid "Nurbs surface in Edit Mode."
msgstr "编辑模式下的NURBS曲面."

#: ../../manual/modeling/surfaces/introduction.rst:19
msgid ""
"As surfaces are 2D, they have two interpolation axes, U (as for curves) and V. It is important to understand that you can control the interpolation rules (knot, order, resolution) *independently* for each of these two dimensions (the U and V fields "
"for all these settings, of course)."
msgstr "由于曲面是2D的，所以他有两个插值坐标轴，U（类似于曲线中的）和V坐标轴，重要的是要知道, 你可以 *分别* 控制两个坐标轴的插值规则（节点，阶数，分辨率）, （当然, 对于所有这些设置项, U和V, 都可以）。"

#: ../../manual/modeling/surfaces/introduction.rst:24
msgid ""
"You may ask yourself \"but the surface appears to be 3D, why is it only 2D?\". In order to be 3D, the object needs to have \"Volume\", and a surface, even when it is closed, does not have volume; it is infinitely thin. If it had a volume the "
"surface would have a thickness (its third dimension). Hence, it is only a 2D object, and has only two interpolation dimensions or axes or coordinates (if you know a bit of math, think of non-euclidean geometry -- well, surfaces are just non-"
"euclidean 2D planes...). To take a more \"real life\" example, you can roll a sheet of paper to create a cylinder; well, even if it \"draws\" a volume, the sheet itself will remain a (nearly...) 2D object!"
msgstr ""
"你也许会问, '但是曲面似乎是3D的, 为什么只有2D?'. 为了成为3D, 物体需要有体积, 和表面, 甚至当它是密闭的的时候, 不再有体积了, 无限的薄. 如果它有体积, 曲面将有厚度(也就是第三个维度). 因此，这只是一个2D物体，并且只有两个插值维度或轴或坐标(如果你知道一点"
"数学，想到了非欧几何-很好，曲面都是非欧2D平面...). 来看更多的\"现实生活\"的示例，你可以卷起一张纸，来创建一个圆柱；然而，即使它\"产生\"了体积，纸片本身仍是一个(几乎...)2D物体！"

#: ../../manual/modeling/surfaces/introduction.rst:34
msgid "In fact, surfaces are very similar to the results you get when :doc:`extruding a curve </modeling/curves/properties/geometry>`."
msgstr "事实上，曲面与你 :doc:`挤出曲线 </modeling/curves/properties/geometry>` 得到的是非常相似的结果."

#: ../../manual/modeling/surfaces/introduction.rst:39
msgid "Visualization"
msgstr "可视化"

#: ../../manual/modeling/surfaces/introduction.rst:41
msgid "There is nearly no difference from NURBS curves, except that the U direction is indicated by yellow grid lines, and the V one is materialized by pink grid lines, as you can see in Fig. :ref:`fig-surface-intro-surface`."
msgstr "除了U向坐标是用黄色的网格线，V向坐标是由粉红网格线标识出来之外，曲面跟NURBS曲线几乎没有区别，你可以看图 :ref:`fig-surface-intro-surface`。"

#: ../../manual/modeling/surfaces/introduction.rst:46
msgid "You can :ref:`hide and reveal <curves-show-hide>` control points just as with curves."
msgstr "你可以 :ref:`隐藏与显示 <curves-show-hide>` 控制点, 这和曲线一样."

